\n| box_width          = \n}}\n\n'''Chris Valletta''' is the co-founder and General Manager of [https://www.mission.com Mission], a consumer products company known for instant-cooling textile technologies. He is also known for playing in  the NFL for three seasons, appearing as a contestant on ''[[The Apprentice (American TV series)|The Apprentice]]'', appearing as an independent contributor on [[Fox News]] and other networks, and for writing the book, [https://www.amazon.com/Team-WORKS-Gridiron-Playbook-Championship/dp/178279669X Team Works!] The Gridiron Playbook for Building a Championship Business Team, with the foreword written by the 45th President of the United States, Donald J. Trump.\n\n==Football career==\n\n===High School and college===\nBorn in New England, Valletta moved to [[Plano, Texas]] in the 1990s, where he attended [[Plano Senior High School]] and played football as an offensive lineman, and was on the Plano Senior Wildcats team that won the 5A State Championship in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|author=${ sender.name } |url=http://frontburner.dmagazine.com/2005/09/21/does-anyone-care-about-the-apprentice/ |title=DOES ANYONE CARE ABOUT THE APPRENTICE? &#124; FrontBurner &#124; D Magazine |publisher=Frontburner.dmagazine.com |date= |accessdate=2013-11-04}}</ref> At Plano, Chris was selected to the prestigious Parade All American Team in 1995.<ref>http://www.ahsfhs.org/Articles/parade1.asp?year=1995</ref> Valletta played football as an offensive linesman at [[Texas A&M University]] from 1997-2000, where he received All-Conference honors.<ref name=\"texags1\">{{cite web|last=Bock |first=Gabe |url=http://v4.texags.com/s/5200/aggie-flashback-with-chris-valletta |title=Aggie Flashback with Chris Valletta &#124; TexAgs |publisher=V4.texags.com |date=2012-05-08 |accessdate=2013-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://startupaggieland.tamu.edu/mentor/chris-valletta/ |title=Chris Valletta &#124; Startup Aggieland |publisher=Startupaggieland.tamu.edu |date=2013-11-21 |accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref> During his time at A&M, he played on the teams that won the Big 12 South Championship in 1997 and the Big 12 Championship in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aggieathletics.com/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=205389912 |title=Texas A&M Conference Championships - Texas A&M Official Athletic Site |publisher=AggieAthletics.com |date= |accessdate=2013-11-04}}</ref> On November 18, 1999, the [[Aggie Bonfire]], part of the pregame festivities between Texas A&M and the University of Texas collapsed during construction, killing 12 and injuring 27.<ref name=\"homeland\">{{cite web | last = Cook | first = John Lee, Jr.| title = Bonfire Collapse | publisher = U.S. Department of Homeland Security | url =http://www.usfa.dhs.gov/downloads/pdf/publications/tr-133.pdf | accessdate = 2013-11-01 |format=PDF}}</ref> At the game, held the following Friday, Valletta wrote the names of the 12 students on a shirt beneath his jersey.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3swj0kL9AuAC&pg=PA32&dq=%22chris+valletta%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=XwZ0UvydH8epyAH83oAI&ved=0CEUQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=%22chris%20valletta%22&f=false |title=Texas A&m Aggies - Ken Rappoport - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=2013-11-04}}</ref> Valletta graduated in 2001, with degrees in majoring in speech communication and rhetorical theory, as well as political science. Chris completed the executive program in entrepreneurship from Harvard Business School in 2015. <ref>{{cite web|last=Colloff |first=Pamela |url=http://www.texasmonthly.com/story/ring-fire/page/0/8 |title=Ring of Fire: Page 9 of 11 |publisher=Texas Monthly |date=1999-11-18 |accessdate=2013-11-04}}</ref>\n\n===Professional===\nValletta signed to the [[Tennessee Titans]] in 2001 as an undrafted free agent.<ref>{{cite web|author=Published: April 26, 2001 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/04/26/sports/transactions-039187.html |title=TRANSACTIONS - New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=2001-04-26 |accessdate=2013-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=August 20, 2001 |title=Titans help Thompson celebrate birthday |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=cJdYAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PUQNAAAAIBAJ&pg=3435,6053575&dq=chris+valletta+tennessee+titans&hl=en |newspaper=The Rochester Sentinel |location= |publisher= |accessdate=2013-11-04 }}</ref> He was released in August of the same year, and signed to the [[New Orleans Saints]], where he was released in August 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kffl.com/gnews.php?id=68378-titans---roster-moves |title=Titans &#124; Roster Moves - NFL Hot off the Wire |publisher=Kffl.com |date= |accessdate=2013-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=August 27, 2002 |title=Monday's Sports Transactions |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ZIIjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=WWsFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2988,7124890&dq=chris+valletta+new+orleans+saints&hl=en |newspaper=McCook Daily Gazette |location= |publisher= |accessdate=2013-11-04 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/players/playerpage/237200/chris-valletta |title=NFL |publisher=CBSSports.com |date=2008-06-11 |accessdate=2013-11-04}}</ref> He then joined the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]], playing Offensive Guard and Center, until his release in October 2002.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tam.scout.com/2/67314.html |title=Scout.com: Bucs Make Several Roster Moves |publisher=Tam.scout.com |date=2002-10-01 |accessdate=2013-11-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140416175946/http://tam.scout.com/2/67314.html |archive-date=2014-04-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Tampa Bay went on to win the Super Bowl that season, beating the [[Oakland Raiders]] 48-21 in [[Super Bowl XXXVII]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200301260rai.htm |title=Tampa Bay Buccaneers vs. Oakland Raiders - January 26th, 2003 |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |date=2003-01-26 |accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===KRLD and Big Tree Investments===\nFollowing his retirement from the NFL, Valletta worked in advertising sales at [[KRLD (AM)|KRLD]] News Radio in Dallas where he became the first rookie salesperson of the year in company history. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2005/09/08/new-apprentice-cast-announced/ |title=New 'Apprentice' Cast Announced |publisher=Fox News |date=2005-09-08 |accessdate=2013-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/dallas/stories/2005/09/26/tidbits1.html?page=all |title=DBJ Confidential - Dallas Business Journal |publisher=Bizjournals.com |date= |accessdate=2013-11-04}}</ref> During this time, he started a real estate company called Big Tree Investments LLC.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= |title=Big Tree Investments, Llc - Nevada Company Profile |url=http://www.nvannualreport.com/entities-DLLC-BIG-TREE-INVESTMENTS-LLC.aspx |newspaper=NV Annual Report |location=Nevada |publisher= |accessdate=2013-11-04 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realitytvworld.com/index/articles/person.php?p=578 |title=Chris Valletta - The Apprentice 4 - Contestant Information - Reality TV World - News, information, episode summaries, message boards, chat and games for unscripted television programs |publisher=Reality TV World |date= |accessdate=2013-11-04}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realitytvworld.com/index/articles/story.php?s=3684 |title=NBC reveals the identities of Donald Trump's 'The Apprentice 4' contestants |publisher=Reality TV World |date=2005-08-31 |accessdate=2013-11-04}}</ref>\n\n===Appearance on ''The Apprentice''===\nIn 2005, Valletta was selected for the cast of the fourth season of ''[[The Apprentice (U.S. season 4)|The Apprentice]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=September 6, 2005 |title=Cannon, Trump triumph on TV |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=lCcqAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LkUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2301,4676210&dq=chris+valletta+new+orleans+saints&hl=en |newspaper=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel |location= |publisher= |accessdate=2013-11-04 }}</ref> Following a ratings slide in the show's third season, Valletta was part of a cast that was personally selected by [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sptimes.com/2005/09/01/Artsandentertainment/Trump_puts_his_stamp_.shtml |title=Artsandentertainment: Trump puts his stamp on 'Apprentice' |publisher=Sptimes.com |date=2005-09-01 |accessdate=2013-11-04}}</ref> He was the second contestant fired from the show, after serving as the project manager for the losing team on a task that involved creating a 30-second television commercial and print ads for a new [[Lamborghini]] sports car.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realitytvworld.com/news/chris-valletta-becomes-second-%91apprentice-4%92-contestant-fired-3725.php |title=chris valletta becomes the second apprentice contestant fired |publisher=Reality TV World |date=2005-09-30 |accessdate=2013-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/chris-fired-apprentice-39667.aspx |title=chris valletta fired from the apprentice - Today's News: Our Take |publisher=TVGuide.com |date=2005-10-06 |accessdate=2013-11-04}}</ref> He also appeared on ''[[The Big Idea with Donny Deutsch]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0524022/?ref_=nm_flmg_slf_2 |title=The Big Idea with Donny Deutsch, Episode dated 14 December 2005 |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website=imdb |publisher= |accessdate=3 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n===GoSMILE===\nFollowing his appearance on ''The Apprentice'', Valletta was named the senior director for business development at GoSMILE Inc.<ref>{{cite web |last=Negus |first=Beth |url=http://www.instorecard.com/a/news/news_stories/08-08-14/Tooth_Serum_GoSmile.aspx?CntPageID=1 |title=Loyalty Lab News Stories > Tooth Serum: GoSmile |publisher=Instorecard.com |date=2008-08-14 |accessdate=2013-11-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140416175408/http://www.instorecard.com/a/news/news_stories/08-08-14/Tooth_Serum_GoSmile.aspx?CntPageID=1 |archivedate=2014-04-16 }}</ref> A company that markets tooth-whitening products, GoSMILE was co-founded by Josh Shaw, one of Valletta's fellow Apprentice contestants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realitytvworld.com/realitytvdb/josh-shaw/person-574 |title=Josh Shaw - The Apprentice 4 - Contestant Information - Reality TV World - News, information, episode summaries, message boards, chat and games for unscripted television programs |publisher=Reality TV World |date= |accessdate=2013-11-04}}</ref> GoSMILE was later acquired by investment firm JH Partners.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/41539072/go-smile-seeks-exposure-expansion |title=Go Smile Seeks Exposure With Expansion - Tags: GO Smile Inc. CORPORATIONS - Growth |publisher=Connection.ebscohost.com |date= |accessdate=2013-11-04}}</ref>\n\n===Mission===\nValletta is the co-founder and General Manager of Mission.<ref name=texags1 /> Founded in 2009, the company markets a line of instant cooling products for active consumers who work or play in the heat. The products are conceived, researched and developed by scientists, labor workers and athletes like Serena Williams, Dwayne Wade and Drew Brees, many of whom are also stakeholders in the company.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kinkhabwala |first=Aditi |url=https://www.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702304708604577505153477334814 |title=Endorsing as a Way of Investing - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=2012-07-08 |accessdate=2013-11-04}}</ref><ref name=\"squarespace1\">{{cite web|author=Friday |url=http://nysportsjournalism.squarespace.com/mission-athletecare-scores-big/?SSScrollPosition=3 |title=NYSportsJournalism.com - Mission Athletecare Scores Big |publisher=Nysportsjournalism.squarespace.com |date=2013-01-11 |accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref> The company was named as the Sports Marketer of the Year for 2012 by readers of NYSportsJournalism.<ref name=squarespace1 />\n\n==Affiliations==\nValletta served as the chairman of the Health and Wellness Committee for the NFL Alumni Organization and currently serves as a representative at large for the Association of a Former Students at Texas A&M University and as an Advisor to the McFerrin Center for Entreprenruship at Texas A&M. Valletta also serves on the board of directors for Young Life Ministries in New York City. (NY/NJ).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebookeralbertagency.com/chris-valletta.html |title=Chris Valletta - The Booker Albert Literary Agency |publisher=Thebookeralbertagency.com |date= |accessdate=2013-11-04}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nValletta resides in New York City and is married to cultural intelligence and multicultural marketing expert [[Liliana Gil Valletta]], founder of CIEN Plus. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://latinoconferenceatharvard.com/speaker-bios.html |title=Speaker Bios - 16th Annual Harvard Latino Law, Policy and Business Conference |publisher=Latinoconferenceatharvard.com |date= |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.mission.com/ Mission Instant Cooling Gear]\n*[http://www.teamworksbook.com/ Official Site]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Valletta, Chris}}\n[[Category:People from Plano, Texas]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Texas A&M University alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "replaced: Advisor \u2192 advisor, General Manager \u2192 general manager (2), 1997-2000 \u2192 1997 to 2000, 45th President \u2192 45th president, in Dallas \u2192 in Dallas,,typo(s) fixed: 48-21 \u2192 48\u201321", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chris_Valletta"}
{"title_page": "Myriam El Khomri", "text_new": "{{short description|French politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Myriam El Khomri\n| image=File:Myriam El Khomri par Claude Truong-Ngoc septembre 2014.jpg\n| office        = [[Council of Paris|Councilor of \u00a8Paris]]\n| term_start    = 21 March 2008\n| term_end      = \n| office2        = [[Minister of Social Affairs (France)|French Minister of Labor, Employment, Vocational Training and Social Dialogue]]\n| term_start2    = 2 September 2015\n| term_end2      = 10 May 2017\n| president2     = [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Manuel Valls]]<br>[[Bernard Cazeneuve]]\n| predecessor2   = [[Fran\u00e7ois Rebsamen]]\n| successor2     = [[Muriel P\u00e9nicaud]]\n| office3        = State Secretary for City Policy\n| term_start3    = 2 September 2015\n| term_end3      = 10 May 2017\n| president3     = [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Manuel Valls]]\n| predecessor3   = [[Najat Vallaud-Belkacem]]\n| successor3     = [[H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Geoffroy]]\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1978|02|18|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Rabat]], [[Morocco]]\n| nationality   = [[France|French]]\n| party         = [[Socialist Party (France)|Socialist Party]]\n| alma_mater    = [[University of Bordeaux]]<br>[[Pantheon-Sorbonne University]]\n}}\n\n'''Myriam El Khomri''' (born 18 February 1978) is a [[France|French]] politician. She served as [[Minister of Social Affairs (France)|Minister of Labour]] from 2015 to 2017.\n\n== Early life and education ==\n\nMyriam El Khomri was born on 18 February 1978 in [[Rabat]]. Her father is Moroccan and her mother is from [[Brittany]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ville.gouv.fr/?myriam-el-khomri|title=Ville.gouv.fr - Minist\u00e8re de la Coh\u00e9sion des territoires|website=Ville.gouv.fr - Minist\u00e8re de la Coh\u00e9sion des territoires|accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Libe 2014-10-07\">{{cite news|last1=Nivelle|first1=Pascale|title=Myriam El-Khomri. Son nouveau pari|url=http://www.liberation.fr/france/2014/10/07/myriam-el-khomri-son-nouveau-pari_1116788|accessdate=2 June 2016|work=[[Lib\u00e9ration]]|date=7 October 2014|language=fr}}</ref> .Until the age of nine, she lived in [[Tangier]]. She then moved with her family to [[Thouars]] and then to [[M\u00e9rignac, Gironde|M\u00e9rignac]] <ref name=\"jeuneafrique\">{{cite web|author=Nicolas Michel |url=https://www.jeuneafrique.com/189653/politique/myriam-el-khomri-surveiller-et-pr-venir/|title=\nMyriam El Khomri, monitor and prevent|language=fr|publisher=[[Jeune Afrique]]|date=21 October 2011 |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1995, she studied public law at the [[Montesquieu University]]. She finances her studies with scholarships and holding several jobs <ref name=\"jeuneafrique\"/>. In 1999, she moved to [[Paris]] and continued her law studies at the University of [[Pantheon-Sorbonne University]], where she obtained a specialized graduate diploma (DESS) in political science (political administration) in 2001.\n\n== Political career ==\n\n=== Parisian elected ===\n\nIn March 2008, Myriam El Khomri was elected in the [[18th arrondissement of Paris]], on the [[Daniel Vaillant]]-[[Bertrand Delano\u00eb]]'s list. She has since been a member of the [[Council of Paris]] and from 2008 to 2011, deputy mayor, in charge of all questions relating to child protection and specialized prevention, then from February 18, 2011 to August 27, 2014, date of her entry into government, deputy mayor responsible for all matters relating to prevention and security.\n\nOn April 21, 2008, she was appointed representative of the Council of Paris on the board of directors of the social action center of the City of Paris and then on May 10, 2008 on the supervisory board of the Bullion Pediatrics and Rehabilitation Hospital and on May 26, 2008 to the pupil surveillance committee of the City of Paris.\n\nShe supports [[Martine Aubry]] during the [[2011 French Socialist Party presidential primary|socialist presidential primary]] in 2011. During the [[2012 French legislative election|legislative elections of 2012]], she is the substitute for [[Christophe Caresche]], deputy for the [[Paris's 18th constituency|18th constituency of Paris]] <ref>{{cite web|author=Anne-Sophie Lechevallier |url=https://www.parismatch.com/Actu/Politique/Myriam-El-Khomri-J-ai-enchaine-les-CDD-935313|title=Myriam El Khomri: \"I have chained fixed-term contracts\"|language=fr|publisher=[[Paris Match]]|date=24 March 2016|accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>. \n\nDuring the [[2014 Paris municipal election|2014 municipal election campaign in Paris]], she was one of [[Anne Hidalgo]]'s spokespersons. Approached by the latter to take over from [[Daniel Vaillant]] as mayor of the [[18th arrondissement of Paris]], the outgoing mayor prefers \u00c9ric Lejoindre. She is reappointed as deputy mayor <ref>{{cite web|author=Sonya Faure & Willy Le Devin |url=https://www.liberation.fr/france/2014/08/26/el-khomri-l-evidence-parisienne_1087651|title=El Khomri, the obviousness of Paris|language=fr|publisher=[[Lib\u00e9ration]]|date=26 August 2016|accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>. \n\n=== Secretary of State for the City ===\n\nShe was appointed, from August 26, 2014, Secretary of State for City Policy in the [[Second Valls government]] <ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/2014/08/26/01002-20140826ARTFIG00317-la-liste-nouveau-gouvernement-valls.php|title=The composition of the Valls II government revealed|language=fr|publisher=[[Le Figaro]]|date=26 August 2016|accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>. \n\nThe policy having been defined by the law constructed by [[Fran\u00e7ois Lamy (politician)|Fran\u00e7ois Lamy]] in the [[Ayrault government]], she concentrates its action on communication. She made its first public appearance in [[Nantes]] on September 7, 2014 on the occasion of the foundation of the collective \"Pas sans nous\", coordination of groups of working-class neighborhoods and then increased travel in the field, especially in the municipalities run by the [[National Rally (France)|National Front]].\n\n=== Minister of Labour ===\n[[File:HAND SHAKE 2016-07-14 (27685880883).jpg|thumb|250px|right|Myriam El Khomri in 2016]]\nOn September 2, 2015, Myriam El Khomri was appointed Minister of Labor, Employment, Vocational Training and Social Dialogue, after the resignation of this post from [[Fran\u00e7ois Rebsamen]] <ref>{{cite web|author= Ga\u00e9tan Supertino|url=https://www.europe1.fr/politique/myriam-el-khomri-la-nouvelle-ministre-du-travail-a-du-pain-sur-la-planche-2508821|title=Myriam El Khomri, the new Minister of Labor, has work to do|language=fr|publisher=[[Europe 1]]|date=2 September 2015|accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>. As when she was appointed to the Secretary of State for the City, she was the subject of critical comments, sometimes racist and sexist, on social networks <ref>{{cite web|author= Marion Dautry |url=https://www.rtl.fr/actu/politique/gouvernement-valls-2-myriam-el-khomri-victime-d-attaques-racistes-sur-twitter-7773969970|title=Government Valls 2: Myriam El Khomri victim of racist attacks on Twitter|language=fr|publisher=[[RTL (French radio)|RTL]]|date=28 August 2014|accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\nShe is responsible for presenting at the beginning of 2016 a controversial bill reforming the [[French labour law|legislation relating to work]], with in particular a flexibilisation of working time, the bases of the future personal activity account, measures on occupational medicine and provisions on the restructuring of professional branches.She plans to include provisions to protect self-employed workers on collaborative platforms like [[Uber]] <ref>{{cite web|author= Marie Bellan & Derek Perrotte|url=https://www.lesechos.fr/2016/01/travailleurs-independants-el-khomri-veut-faire-payer-les-plate-formes-internet-195864|title=Self-employed workers: El Khomri wants to charge Internet platforms|language=fr|publisher=[[Les Echos (France)|Les Echos]]|date=6 January 2016|accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>.\nThe Law sparks strike action. In 2016, the French cabinet gave the prime minister [[Manuel Valls]] permission to bypass parliament and enact a sweeping set of labour reforms known widely as the [[El Khomri law]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-36259120|title=French labour reforms: Government to force plan through|publisher=BBC News|date=2016-05-10|accessdate=2016-05-25}}</ref>\n\n== After government ==\n\nOn December 8, 2016, Myriam El Khomri was invested by [[Socialist Party (France)|PS]]'s activists for the [[2017 French legislative election|2017 legislative elections]] in the [[Paris's 18th constituency|18th constituency of Paris]] <ref>{{cite web|author= Nicolas Maviel|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/paris-75/paris-75005/legislatives-les-militants-ps-ont-choisi-myriam-el-khomri-09-12-2016-6436683.php|title=Legislative: PS activists have chosen Myriam El Khomri|language=fr|publisher=[[Le Parisien]]|date=9 December 2016|accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>. She calls to vote for [[Emmanuel Macron]] in the second round. [[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]] does not oppose him a candidate during the legislative elections that follow despite the mobilization of party activists against this hypothesis. She announced that she wanted to carry the values \u200b\u200bof the left within the presidential majority and faced [[Pierre-Yves Bournazel]], [[The Republicans (France)|LR]]'s candidate, who also said he supported the presidential majority. She was beaten at the end of the second round, with 53.6% against 46.4%.\n\nShe then converted to the consulting field by creating in November 2017 a business consultancy, MEK Conseil. \nIn May 2018, she also became senior advisor to [[The Adecco Group|Lee Hecht Harrison Altedia]], then in March 2019, she joined the insurance brokerage group Siaci Saint Honor\u00e9 as director of the Consulting division of its consulting and strategy subsidiary S2H Consulting <ref>{{cite web|author= Shahinez Benabed|url=https://www.acteurspublics.fr/nomination/lex-ministre-du-travail-myriam-el-khomri-recrutee-par-un-courtier-en-assurances|title=\nFormer Labor Minister Myriam El Khomri recruited by an insurance broker|language=fr|publisher=Acteurs publics|date=22 March 2019|accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\nIn March 2018, she performed with [[Roselyne Bachelot]] and [[Marl\u00e8ne Schiappa]] a representation of [[The Vagina Monologues]] at the [[Bobino|Bobino theater]]. The profits of the show go to the Feminist Collective against rape <ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/societe/monologues-du-vagin-schiappa-bachelot-et-el-khomri-reunies-sur-scene_1990675.html|title=\n\"Vagina monologues\": Schiappa, Bachelot and El Khomri together on stage|language=fr|publisher=[[L'Express]]|date=8 March 2018|accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\nIn July 2019, the Minister of Solidarity and Health [[Agn\u00e8s Buzyn]] appoints Myriam El Khomri to head a mission on the attractiveness of professions in the elderly, with the aim of combating the shortage of personnel in this sector <ref>{{cite web|author=B\u00e9atrice J\u00e9r\u00f4me|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/societe/article/2019/06/13/myriam-el-khomri-va-piloter-une-mission-sur-les-metiers-du-grand-age_5475855_3224.html|title=Myriam El Khomri will lead a mission on the professions of old age|language=fr|publisher=[[Le Monde]]|date=13 June 2019|accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khomri, Myriam}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Socialist Party (France) politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Rabat]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of France]]\n[[Category:French people of Moroccan descent]]\n[[Category:Moroccan people of French descent]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of France]]\n[[Category:21st-century French politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century French women politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Myriam El Khomri\n| image=File:Myriam El Khomri par Claude Truong-Ngoc septembre 2014.jpg\n| office        = [[Council of Paris|Councilor of \u00a8Paris]]\n| term_start    = 21 March 2008\n| term_end      = \n| office2        = [[Minister of Social Affairs (France)|French Minister of Labor, Employment, Vocational Training and Social Dialogue]]\n| term_start2    = 2 September 2015\n| term_end2      = 10 May 2017\n| president2     = [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Manuel Valls]]<br>[[Bernard Cazeneuve]]\n| predecessor2   = [[Fran\u00e7ois Rebsamen]]\n| successor2     = [[Muriel P\u00e9nicaud]]\n| office3        = State Secretary for City Policy\n| term_start3    = 2 September 2015\n| term_end3      = 10 May 2017\n| president3     = [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Manuel Valls]]\n| predecessor3   = [[Najat Vallaud-Belkacem]]\n| successor3     = [[H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Geoffroy]]\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1978|02|18|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Rabat]], [[Morocco]]\n| nationality   = [[France|French]]\n| party         = [[Socialist Party (France)|Socialist Party]]\n| alma_mater    = [[University of Bordeaux]]<br>[[Pantheon-Sorbonne University]]\n}}\n\n'''Myriam El Khomri''' (born 18 February 1978) is a [[France|French]] politician. She served as [[Minister of Social Affairs (France)|Minister of Labour]] from 2015 to 2017.\n\n== Early life and education ==\n\nMyriam El Khomri was born on 18 February 1978 in [[Rabat]]. Her father is Moroccan and her mother is from [[Brittany]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ville.gouv.fr/?myriam-el-khomri|title=Ville.gouv.fr - Minist\u00e8re de la Coh\u00e9sion des territoires|website=Ville.gouv.fr - Minist\u00e8re de la Coh\u00e9sion des territoires|accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Libe 2014-10-07\">{{cite news|last1=Nivelle|first1=Pascale|title=Myriam El-Khomri. Son nouveau pari|url=http://www.liberation.fr/france/2014/10/07/myriam-el-khomri-son-nouveau-pari_1116788|accessdate=2 June 2016|work=[[Lib\u00e9ration]]|date=7 October 2014|language=fr}}</ref> .Until the age of nine, she lived in [[Tangier]]. She then moved with her family to [[Thouars]] and then to [[M\u00e9rignac, Gironde|M\u00e9rignac]] <ref name=\"jeuneafrique\">{{cite web|author=Nicolas Michel |url=https://www.jeuneafrique.com/189653/politique/myriam-el-khomri-surveiller-et-pr-venir/|title=\nMyriam El Khomri, monitor and prevent|language=fr|publisher=[[Jeune Afrique]]|date=21 October 2011 |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1995, she studied public law at the [[Montesquieu University]]. She finances her studies with scholarships and holding several jobs <ref name=\"jeuneafrique\"/>. In 1999, she moved to [[Paris]] and continued her law studies at the University of [[Pantheon-Sorbonne University]], where she obtained a specialized graduate diploma (DESS) in political science (political administration) in 2001.\n\n== Political career ==\n\n=== Parisian elected ===\n\nIn March 2008, Myriam El Khomri was elected in the [[18th arrondissement of Paris]], on the [[Daniel Vaillant]]-[[Bertrand Delano\u00eb]]'s list. She has since been a member of the [[Council of Paris]] and from 2008 to 2011, deputy mayor, in charge of all questions relating to child protection and specialized prevention, then from February 18, 2011 to August 27, 2014, date of her entry into government, deputy mayor responsible for all matters relating to prevention and security.\n\nOn April 21, 2008, she was appointed representative of the Council of Paris on the board of directors of the social action center of the City of Paris and then on May 10, 2008 on the supervisory board of the Bullion Pediatrics and Rehabilitation Hospital and on May 26, 2008 to the pupil surveillance committee of the City of Paris.\n\nShe supports [[Martine Aubry]] during the [[2011 French Socialist Party presidential primary|socialist presidential primary]] in 2011. During the [[2012 French legislative election|legislative elections of 2012]], she is the substitute for [[Christophe Caresche]], deputy for the [[Paris's 18th constituency|18th constituency of Paris]] <ref>{{cite web|author=Anne-Sophie Lechevallier |url=https://www.parismatch.com/Actu/Politique/Myriam-El-Khomri-J-ai-enchaine-les-CDD-935313|title=Myriam El Khomri: \"I have chained fixed-term contracts\"|language=fr|publisher=[[Paris Match]]|date=24 March 2016|accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>. \n\nDuring the [[2014 Paris municipal election|2014 municipal election campaign in Paris]], she was one of [[Anne Hidalgo]]'s spokespersons. Approached by the latter to take over from [[Daniel Vaillant]] as mayor of the [[18th arrondissement of Paris]], the outgoing mayor prefers \u00c9ric Lejoindre. She is reappointed as deputy mayor <ref>{{cite web|author=Sonya Faure & Willy Le Devin |url=https://www.liberation.fr/france/2014/08/26/el-khomri-l-evidence-parisienne_1087651|title=El Khomri, the obviousness of Paris|language=fr|publisher=[[Lib\u00e9ration]]|date=26 August 2016|accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>. \n\n=== Secretary of State for the City ===\n\nShe was appointed, from August 26, 2014, Secretary of State for City Policy in the [[Second Valls government]] <ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/2014/08/26/01002-20140826ARTFIG00317-la-liste-nouveau-gouvernement-valls.php|title=The composition of the Valls II government revealed|language=fr|publisher=[[Le Figaro]]|date=26 August 2016|accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>. \n\nThe policy having been defined by the law constructed by [[Fran\u00e7ois Lamy (politician)|Fran\u00e7ois Lamy]] in the [[Ayrault government]], she concentrates its action on communication. She made its first public appearance in [[Nantes]] on September 7, 2014 on the occasion of the foundation of the collective \"Pas sans nous\", coordination of groups of working-class neighborhoods and then increased travel in the field, especially in the municipalities run by the [[National Rally (France)|National Front]].\n\n=== Minister of Labour ===\n[[File:HAND SHAKE 2016-07-14 (27685880883).jpg|thumb|250px|right|Myriam El Khomri in 2016]]\nOn September 2, 2015, Myriam El Khomri was appointed Minister of Labor, Employment, Vocational Training and Social Dialogue, after the resignation of this post from [[Fran\u00e7ois Rebsamen]] <ref>{{cite web|author= Ga\u00e9tan Supertino|url=https://www.europe1.fr/politique/myriam-el-khomri-la-nouvelle-ministre-du-travail-a-du-pain-sur-la-planche-2508821|title=Myriam El Khomri, the new Minister of Labor, has work to do|language=fr|publisher=[[Europe 1]]|date=2 September 2015|accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>. As when she was appointed to the Secretary of State for the City, she was the subject of critical comments, sometimes racist and sexist, on social networks <ref>{{cite web|author= Marion Dautry |url=https://www.rtl.fr/actu/politique/gouvernement-valls-2-myriam-el-khomri-victime-d-attaques-racistes-sur-twitter-7773969970|title=Government Valls 2: Myriam El Khomri victim of racist attacks on Twitter|language=fr|publisher=[[RTL (French radio)|RTL]]|date=28 August 2014|accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\nShe is responsible for presenting at the beginning of 2016 a controversial bill reforming the [[French labour law|legislation relating to work]], with in particular a flexibilisation of working time, the bases of the future personal activity account, measures on occupational medicine and provisions on the restructuring of professional branches.She plans to include provisions to protect self-employed workers on collaborative platforms like [[Uber]] <ref>{{cite web|author= Marie Bellan & Derek Perrotte|url=https://www.lesechos.fr/2016/01/travailleurs-independants-el-khomri-veut-faire-payer-les-plate-formes-internet-195864|title=Self-employed workers: El Khomri wants to charge Internet platforms|language=fr|publisher=[[Les Echos (France)|Les Echos]]|date=6 January 2016|accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>.\nThe Law sparks strike action. In 2016, the French cabinet gave the prime minister [[Manuel Valls]] permission to bypass parliament and enact a sweeping set of labour reforms known widely as the [[El Khomri law]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-36259120|title=French labour reforms: Government to force plan through|publisher=BBC News|date=2016-05-10|accessdate=2016-05-25}}</ref>\n\n== After government ==\n\nOn December 8, 2016, Myriam El Khomri was invested by [[Socialist Party (France)|PS]]'s activists for the [[2017 French legislative election|2017 legislative elections]] in the [[Paris's 18th constituency|18th constituency of Paris]] <ref>{{cite web|author= Nicolas Maviel|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/paris-75/paris-75005/legislatives-les-militants-ps-ont-choisi-myriam-el-khomri-09-12-2016-6436683.php|title=Legislative: PS activists have chosen Myriam El Khomri|language=fr|publisher=[[Le Parisien]]|date=9 December 2016|accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>. She calls to vote for [[Emmanuel Macron]] in the second round. [[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]] does not oppose him a candidate during the legislative elections that follow despite the mobilization of party activists against this hypothesis. She announced that she wanted to carry the values \u200b\u200bof the left within the presidential majority and faced [[Pierre-Yves Bournazel]], [[The Republicans (France)|LR]]'s candidate, who also said he supported the presidential majority. She was beaten at the end of the second round, with 53.6% against 46.4%.\n\nShe then converted to the consulting field by creating in November 2017 a business consultancy, MEK Conseil. \nIn May 2018, she also became senior advisor to [[The Adecco Group|Lee Hecht Harrison Altedia]], then in March 2019, she joined the insurance brokerage group Siaci Saint Honor\u00e9 as director of the Consulting division of its consulting and strategy subsidiary S2H Consulting <ref>{{cite web|author= Shahinez Benabed|url=https://www.acteurspublics.fr/nomination/lex-ministre-du-travail-myriam-el-khomri-recrutee-par-un-courtier-en-assurances|title=\nFormer Labor Minister Myriam El Khomri recruited by an insurance broker|language=fr|publisher=Acteurs publics|date=22 March 2019|accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\nIn March 2018, she performed with [[Roselyne Bachelot]] and [[Marl\u00e8ne Schiappa]] a representation of [[The Vagina Monologues]] at the [[Bobino|Bobino theater]]. The profits of the show go to the Feminist Collective against rape <ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/societe/monologues-du-vagin-schiappa-bachelot-et-el-khomri-reunies-sur-scene_1990675.html|title=\n\"Vagina monologues\": Schiappa, Bachelot and El Khomri together on stage|language=fr|publisher=[[L'express]]|date=8 March 2018|accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\nIn July 2019, the Minister of Solidarity and Health [[Agn\u00e8s Buzyn]] appoints Myriam El Khomri to head a mission on the attractiveness of professions in the elderly, with the aim of combating the shortage of personnel in this sector <ref>{{cite web|author=B\u00e9atrice J\u00e9r\u00f4me|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/societe/article/2019/06/13/myriam-el-khomri-va-piloter-une-mission-sur-les-metiers-du-grand-age_5475855_3224.html|title=Myriam El Khomri will lead a mission on the professions of old age|language=fr|publisher=[[Le Monde]]|date=13 June 2019|accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khomri, Myriam}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Socialist Party (France) politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Rabat]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of France]]\n[[Category:French people of Moroccan descent]]\n[[Category:Moroccan people of French descent]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of France]]\n[[Category:21st-century French politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century French women politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling correction; redirect bypass fromL'expresstoL'Expressusingpopups", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Myriam_El_Khomri"}
{"title_page": "Miss South Africa 2014", "text_new": "{{Beauty pageant \n| photo = \n| caption = \n| winner = '''[[Rolene Strauss]]'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2014-03-30-rolene-strauss-crowned-miss-south-africa-2014/|title=Rolene Strauss crowned Miss SA 2014|website=Mail & Guardian (South Africa)|date=30 March 2014|access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n| represented = [[Volksrust]]\n| date = March 30, 2014\n| presenters = Elana Afrika-Bredenkamp\n| acts = Mi Casa, Bucie and Matthew Mole\n| entrants = 12\n| placements = 5\n| venue = [[Sun City Superbowl]], [[Rustenburg]], [[South Africa]]\n| broadcaster = [[DStv]]\n| withdraws = \n| congeniality = Abigail de Jager \n| photogenic =\n| before = [[Miss South Africa 2012|2012]]\n| next = [[Miss South Africa 2015|2015]]\n}}\n'''Miss South Africa 2014''', the 59th edition of the [[Miss South Africa]] pageant, was held on March 30, 2014 at [[Sun City Superbowl]].\n\nThe pageant was broadcast on [[DStv]] on [[Mzansi Magic]], and was hosted by television and radio personality Elana Afrika-Bredenkamp. The final was contested by 12 girls who were selected after weeks of grueling challenges at Sun City International.  \n\nThe pageant was won by [[Rolene Strauss]] who, in the December of the same year, was also crowned [[Miss World 2014|Miss World]].<ref>{{Cite web|language=fr|url=https://www.nouvelobs.com/monde/20141214.AFP3293/miss-afrique-du-sud-rolene-strauss-couronnee-miss-monde-2014.html|title=Miss Afrique du Sud, Rolene Strauss, couronn\u00e9e Miss Monde 2014|website=L'Obs|date=14 December 2014|access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref> Strauss' winning of the Miss World title made her ineligible for Miss Universe; this led to Miss South Africa 2014 first runner up Ziphozakhe Zokufa being crowned Miss South Africa,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ewn.co.za/2014/12/16/New-Miss-SA-to-be-crowned-tomorrow|title=New Miss SA to be Crowned Tomorrow| publisher=Eyewitness News| accessdate=January 24, 2014|first=Nomsa|last=Mdhluli}}</ref> to allow Zokufa  to compete for the [[Miss Universe 2014]] crown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://randburgsun.co.za/246318/zokufa-represents-sa-in-the-miss-universe-pageant/|title=Zokufa represents SA in the Miss Universe pageant|website=Randburg Sun|date=9 January 2015|access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Results ==\n\n{| class=\"sortable\" border=\"5\" cellpadding=\"3\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #FFFFFF; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#787878\" colspan=10 align=\"center\"\n|width=\"220\"|<span style=\"color:#FFFFFF\">'''Final Results'''</span>||width=\"150\"|<span style=\"color:#FFFFFF\">'''Contestant'''</span>\n|-\n| <center>'''Miss South Africa 2014'''</center>\n|\n*'''[[Rolene Strauss]]'''\n|-\n| <center>'''1st Princess'''</center>\n|\n*Ziphozakhe Zokufa\n|-\n|<center>''' 2nd Princess'''</center>\n|\n* Matlala Mokoko\n|-\n| <center>'''Top 5'''</center>\n|\n*Anzel Stofberg\n*Tidimalo Sehlako\n|}\n\n== Contestants ==\n{| class=\"sortable\" border=\"5\" cellpadding=\"3\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #FFFFFF; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#787878\" colspan=10 align=\"center\"\n|width=\"150\"|<span style=\"color:#FFFFFF\">'''Contestant'''</span>||width=\"30\"|<span style=\"color:#FFFFFF\">'''Age'''</span>||width=\"30\"|<span style=\"color:#FFFFFF\">'''Height'''</span>||width=\"100\"|<span style=\"color:#FFFFFF\">'''Province'''</span>||width=\"100\"|<span style=\"color:#FFFFFF\">'''Hometown'''</span> \n|-\n| Abigail de Jager || 19 || {{height|cm=181}} || [[Mpumalanga]] || [[Nelspruit]]\n|-\n| Anzel Stofberg || 22 || {{height|cm=175}} || [[Western Cape]] || [[Stellenbosch]]\n|-\n| Caylene Marais || 23 || {{height|cm=173}} || [[Gauteng]] || [[Roodepoort]]\n|-\n| Dipalesa Mbola || 22 || {{height|cm=174}} || [[Free State (province)|Free State]] || [[Bloemfontein]]\n|-\n| Jade H\u00fcbner || 21 || {{height|cm=170}} || [[Western Cape]] || [[Cape Town]] \n|-\n| Julia Petersen || 22 || {{height|cm=176}} || [[KwaZulu Natal]] || [[Durban]]\n|-\n| Matlala Mokoko || 23 || {{height|cm=182}} || [[Limpopo]] || [[Limpopo|Marogwe]]\n|-\n| Mishka Patel || 21 || {{height|cm=182}} || [[Western Cape]] || [[Cape Town]] \n|-\n| '''[[Rolene Strauss]]'''<ref>{{Cite web|first=Freya|last=Drohan|url=https://www.independent.ie/style/beauty/miss-south-africa-rolene-strauss-is-crowned-miss-world-2014-30834831.html|title=Miss South Africa Rolene Strauss is crowned Miss World 2014|date=14 December 2014|website=Independent.ie|access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref> || 22 || {{height|cm=177}} || [[Mpumalanga]] || [[Volksrust]]\n|-\n| Tidimalo Sehlako || 22 || {{height|cm=165}} || [[Gauteng]] || [[Vereeniging]]\n|-\n| Tshegofatso Monggae || 22 || {{height|cm=181}} || [[Gauteng]] || [[Roodepoort]]\n|-\n| Ziphozakhe Zokufa<ref>{{Cite web|first=Zesuliwe|last=Hadebe|url=https://southerncourier.co.za/50435/new-miss-sa-crowned-2/|title=New Miss SA crowned|website=|date=17 December 2014|access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref> || 22 || {{height|cm=172}} || [[Eastern Cape]] || [[Port Elizabeth]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== Special prizes ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Prize\n! Contestant\n|-\n| Miss Congeniality\n| Abigail de Jager\n|-\n|}\n\n== Judges ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! scope=col colspan=\"2\" | Member\n|-\n| [[Anele Mdoda]] || Radio and TV personality \n|-\n| [[Bonang Matheba]] || Radio and TV personality\n|-\n| [[Kojo Baffoe]] || Editor of Destiny Man\n|-\n| [[Amy Kleinhans]] || Miss South Africa 1992 \n|-\n| Pnina Fenster ||  Editor-in-Chief of Glamour Magazine\n|-\n|}\n\n== Music and entertainment ==\n* [[Bucie]]\n* [[Mi Casa]]\n* [[Matthew Mole]]\n== Crossovers ==\nContestants who previously competed or will be competing at international beauty pageants: \n\n;[[Miss World]]\n*[[Miss World 2014|2014]]: [[File:Flag of Mpumalanga Province.svg|22px|border]] '''[[Mpumalanga]]''' \u2013 [[Rolene Strau