{"title_page": "Frances K. Conley", "text_new": "{{short description|American neurosrogeon}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Frances \"Fran\" Krauskopf Conley\n| image       = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1940|08|12}}\n| birth_place = [[Palo Alto, California]]\n| death_date  = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1940|08|12}} or {{Death-date and age|Month DD, YYYY|Month DD, YYYY}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = \n| nationality = American\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = \n| occupation  = Professor of neurosurgery\n}}\n\n'''Frances''' \"'''Fran'''\" '''Krauskopf Conley''' (born August 12, 1940 in [[Palo Alto, California]]) is a professor of [[neurosurgery]] at [[Stanford University]].  She is the author of ''Walking Out on the Boys''\n(Ferrar, Straus and Giroux 1998), the story of her protest of [[misogyny]]\nat the University hospital.<ref name=\"nytreview\">{{cite news \n  | last = Jacoby\n  | first = Susan\n  | coauthors = \n  | title = Hospital Harassment: A woman neurosurgeon writes about sexism among doctors\n  | newspaper = New York Times\n  | location =\n  | pages = \n  | language = \n  | publisher = \n  | date = April 26, 1998\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/04/26/reviews/980426.26jacobyt.html\n  | accessdate = 2020-01-03}}\n</ref>\n\nConley was born in 1940 to Konrad Bates Krauskopf and Kathryn McCune Krauskopf. She was a crucial figure in the advancement of women in\nAmerican medicine.\n\n==Medical career==\nIn 1966 she became the first woman to pursue a surgical internship at Stanford Hospital, in 1975 she became the first female faculty member at Stanford in any surgical department, in 1977, she became the fifth woman to become a board certified neurosurgeon in the United States,<ref name=\"wins\">{{cite web\n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | authorlink = \n  | coauthors = \n  | title = Spotlight on WINS: Frances K. Conley, MD\n  | work = \n  | publisher = Women in Neurosurgery\n  | year = 1998\n  | url = http://www.neurosurgerywins.org/spotlight/conley_frances_k.html\n  | doi = \n  | accessdate = 2012-01-03\n  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120216102742/http://www.neurosurgerywins.org/spotlight/conley_frances_k.html\n  | archive-date = 2012-02-16\n  | url-status = dead\n  }}</ref>\nin 1982 the first woman to be granted a tenured professorship in neurosurgery at a\nU.S. medical school,<ref name=\"nytreview\"/> and in 1986, the first to have a\nfull professorship.<ref name=\"nih\">\n{{cite web\n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | authorlink = \n  | coauthors = \n  | title = Changing the Face of Medicine: Dr. Frances K. Conley\n  | work = \n  | publisher = U.S. National Library of Medicine, National Institutes of Health\n  | date = \n  | url = https://www.nlm.nih.gov/changingthefaceofmedicine/physicians/biography_68.html\n  | doi = \n  | accessdate = 2012-01-03}}\n</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nShe essentially grew up on the [[Stanford University|Stanford]] campus where her father was a professor of geochemistry. She decided in her early teenage years that she wanted to become a doctor even though the housewife stigma was the norm of the time.\n\nShe attended [[Bryn Mawr College]] in Lower Merion Township, Pennsylvania. In her junior year, she returned to Stanford. She then entered medical school at Stanford in 1961. Her class consisted of twelve women and sixty men and she noticed that male and female students were treated much differently. During her time at Stanford medical school, she quickly realized her true passion: surgery. Surgery was a male-dominated sub-field of medicine, but this did not stop Conley from pursuing it and she ended up finishing her M.D. degree in 1966.<ref name=\"nih\"/>\n\nShe met her future husband, [[Phil Conley]], during her time at Stanford.\n\n==Stanford University==\nIn June 1991, she publicly resigned in protest over the work environment that included sexist attitudes and outright sexual\nharassment that culminated in the appointment of Dr. Gerald Silverberg as acting chair of the department of neurosurgery despite accusations against him of sexual harassment by two clerical staff.  Several months later, after promises of changes in University procedures and policies on sexism, she rescinded her resignation in an effort to ensure the changes might actually be implemented.<ref name=\"nytreview\"/>\n\nHer book ''Walking Out on the Boys'' spotlit misogyny at one of the nation's leading universities and led to changes in programming\nthroughout the country.\n\nShe was also chair of the Stanford University Academic Council in 1997/1998 and is now retired.<ref name=\"nih\"/>  In her later,\nexecutive, appointments she worked to enact the reforms that had long been asserted to be unnecessary, already achieved, or imminent.\n\n== ''Walking Out on the Boys'' ==\nWhen Conley resigned from Stanford University, her book ''Walking Out on the Boys'' was released and provided a very in depth and firsthand look at the sexism that really went on at the university.<ref>{{cite book|last=Conley|first=Frances|title=Walking Out on the Boys|url=https://archive.org/details/walkingoutonboys00conl|url-access=registration|year=1998|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|location=New York}}</ref>  Conley also boldly uses the real names of the biggest perpetrators. This book offers some behind-the-scenes views of the medical school located at Stanford including certain labs and research. Her resignation and the release of this book not only created some public towards her, but also towards other instances of sexism across the country that not only occur in medical schools of universities but throughout hospitals and research environments as well.<ref>{{cite news|last=Conley|first=Frances|title=Sexism in the Workplace|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=17 June 1991}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1971, Conley was the first official women's winner of the [[Bay to Breakers]] 12K footrace with a time of 50:45. Her husband, [[Phil Conley]], was also an athlete, representing the United States in [[Athletics at the 1956 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's javelin throw|track and field at the 1956 Olympics]].<ref name=\"nih\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bryn Mawr College]]\n*[[Stanford University School of Medicine]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,973360-1,00.html Interview in ''TIME''] July 8, 1991.\n*[https://www.nlm.nih.gov/changingthefaceofmedicine/physicians/biography_68.html Biography from U.S. National Library of Medicine]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Conley, Frances}}\n[[Category:Stanford Graduate School of Business alumni]]\n[[Category:Stanford University School of Medicine faculty]]\n[[Category:American women writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American neurosrogeon}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Frances \"Fran\" Krauskopf Conley\n| image       = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1940|08|12}}\n| birth_place = [[Palo Alto, California]]\n| death_date  = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1940|08|12}} or {{Death-date and age|Month DD, YYYY|Month DD, YYYY}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = \n| nationality = American\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = \n| occupation  = Professor of neurosurgery\n}}\n\n'''Frances''' \"'''Fran'''\" '''Krauskopf Conley''' (born August 12, 1940 in [[Palo Alto, California]]) is a professor of [[neurosurgery]] at [[Stanford University]].  She is the author of ''Walking Out on the Boys''\n(Ferrar, Straus and Giroux 1998), the story of her protest of [[misogyny]]\nat the University hospital.<ref name=\"nytreview\">{{cite news \n  | last = Jacoby\n  | first = Susan\n  | coauthors = \n  | title = Hospital Harassment: A woman neurosurgeon writes about sexism among doctors\n  | newspaper = New York Times\n  | location =\n  | pages = \n  | language = \n  | publisher = \n  | date = April 26, 1998\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/04/26/reviews/980426.26jacobyt.html\n  | accessdate = 2020-01-03}}\n</ref>\n\nConley was born in 1940 to Konrad Bates Krauskopf and Kathryn McCune Krauskopf. She was a crucial figure in the advancement of women in\nAmerican medicine.\n\n==Medical career==\nIn 1966 she became the first woman to pursue a surgical internship at Stanford Hospital, in 1975 she became the first female faculty member at Stanford in any surgical department, in 1977, she became the fifth woman to become a board certified neurosurgeon in the United States,<ref name=\"wins\">{{cite web\n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | authorlink = \n  | coauthors = \n  | title = Spotlight on WINS: Frances K. Conley, MD\n  | work = \n  | publisher = Women in Neurosurgery\n  | year = 1998\n  | url = http://www.neurosurgerywins.org/spotlight/conley_frances_k.html\n  | doi = \n  | accessdate = 2012-01-03\n  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120216102742/http://www.neurosurgerywins.org/spotlight/conley_frances_k.html\n  | archive-date = 2012-02-16\n  | url-status = dead\n  }}</ref>\nin 1982 the first woman to be granted a tenured professorship in neurosurgery at a\nU.S. medical school,<ref name=\"nytreview\"/> and in 1986, the first to have a\nfull professorship.<ref name=\"nih\">\n{{cite web\n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | authorlink = \n  | coauthors = \n  | title = Changing the Face of Medicine: Dr. Frances K. Conley\n  | work = \n  | publisher = U.S. National Library of Medicine, National Institutes of Health\n  | date = \n  | url = https://www.nlm.nih.gov/changingthefaceofmedicine/physicians/biography_68.html\n  | doi = \n  | accessdate = 2012-01-03}}\n</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nShe essentially grew up on the [[Stanford University|Stanford]] campus where her father was a professor of geochemistry. She decided in her early teenage years that she wanted to become a doctor even though the housewife stigma was the norm of the time.\n\nShe attended [[Bryn Mawr College]] in Lower Merion Township, Pennsylvania. In her junior year, she returned to Stanford. She then entered medical school at Stanford in 1961. Her class consisted of twelve women and sixty men and she noticed that male and female students were treated much differently. During her time at Stanford]] medical school, she quickly realized her true passion: surgery. Surgery was a male-dominated sub-field of medicine, but this did not stop Conley from pursuing it and she ended up finishing her M.D. degree in 1966.<ref name=\"nih\"/>\n\nShe met her future husband, [[Phil Conley]], during her time at Stanford.\n\n==Stanford University==\nIn June 1991, she publicly resigned in protest over the work environment that included sexist attitudes and outright sexual\nharassment that culminated in the appointment of Dr. Gerald Silverberg as acting chair of the department of neurosurgery despite accusations against him of sexual harassment by two clerical staff.  Several months later, after promises of changes in University procedures and policies on sexism, she rescinded her resignation in an effort to ensure the changes might actually be implemented.<ref name=\"nytreview\"/>\n\nHer book ''Walking Out on the Boys'' spotlit misogyny at one of the nation's leading universities and led to changes in programming\nthroughout the country.\n\nShe was also chair of the Stanford University Academic Council in 1997/1998 and is now retired.<ref name=\"nih\"/>  In her later,\nexecutive, appointments she worked to enact the reforms that had long been asserted to be unnecessary, already achieved, or imminent.\n\n== ''Walking Out on the Boys'' ==\nWhen Conley resigned from Stanford University, her book ''Walking Out on the Boys'' was released and provided a very in depth and firsthand look at the sexism that really went on at the university.<ref>{{cite book|last=Conley|first=Frances|title=Walking Out on the Boys|url=https://archive.org/details/walkingoutonboys00conl|url-access=registration|year=1998|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|location=New York}}</ref>  Conley also boldly uses the real names of the biggest perpetrators. This book offers some behind-the-scenes views of the medical school located at Stanford including certain labs and research. Her resignation and the release of this book not only created some public towards her, but also towards other instances of sexism across the country that not only occur in medical schools of universities but throughout hospitals and research environments as well.<ref>{{cite news|last=Conley|first=Frances|title=Sexism in the Workplace|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=17 June 1991}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1971, Conley was the first official women's winner of the [[Bay to Breakers]] 12K footrace with a time of 50:45. Her husband, [[Phil Conley]], was also an athlete, representing the United States in [[Athletics at the 1956 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's javelin throw|track and field at the 1956 Olympics]].<ref name=\"nih\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bryn Mawr College]]\n*[[Stanford University School of Medicine]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,973360-1,00.html Interview in ''TIME''] July 8, 1991.\n*[https://www.nlm.nih.gov/changingthefaceofmedicine/physicians/biography_68.html Biography from U.S. National Library of Medicine]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Conley, Frances}}\n[[Category:Stanford Graduate School of Business alumni]]\n[[Category:Stanford University School of Medicine faculty]]\n[[Category:American women writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n", "name_user": "Ombudsman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:rm errata", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frances_K._Conley"}
{"title_page": "Indigenous people in video games", "text_new": "[[Indigenous people]] have a long history of collaborating on the creation of [[video game]]s.<ref name=\"vimeo.com\">https://vimeo.com/128110465</ref> It has only been with the release of [[Never Alone (video game)|Never Alone]] though that broad media attention has been paid to these projects.<ref>A Tribe Called Geek's third podcast called \"Indigenous Gaming\" http://atribecalledgeek.com/tag/video-games/ ; see also http://ca.ign.com/articles/2015/01/16/the-rise-of-indigenous-storytelling-in-games</ref> There have been a growing number of game gatherings and community organizing around Indigenous games happening in the United States and Canada.<ref name=\"linkedin.com\">https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/natives-game-dev-gathering-elizabeth-lapens%C3%A9e</ref><ref name=\"pinnguaq.com\">http://pinnguaq.com/blog-all/120-evening-celebrate</ref> Indigenous creators of video games have been featured in the DIGITAL MEDIA ART+CADE as part of imagineNATIVE<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.imaginenative.org/home/node/4546 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-12-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927051603/http://www.imaginenative.org/home/node/4546 |archive-date=2015-09-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and in ''Memories of the Future/Souvenirs du futur'' at SAW Video Media Art Centre in Ottawa.<ref>http://www.sawvideo.com/event/memories-future</ref> Many early video games that depicted Indigenous people misrepresented them and perpetuated negative stereotypes (see [[Custer's Revenge]]).<ref>http://www.cbc.ca/news/aboriginal/indigenous-video-game-designer-takes-stand-against-custer-s-revenge-1.2851104</ref> Video games created by Indigenous people enable the creators to self-determine how they are represented<ref>http://www.content.alternative.ac.nz/index.php/alternative/article/view/274</ref>.\n\n== Games where Indigenous people represent themselves ==\nIndigenous people have been involved in a range of projects where they have the opportunity to depict themselves. These games range in the style of the collaboration from games that consult with a single Indigenous person to games that are entirely developed and designed by Indigenous people.<ref name=\"vimeo.com\"/> \n* [http://www.7generationgames.com/ 7 Generation Games] ([http://www.7generationgames.com/products/ Spirit Lake] [2013], [http://www.7generationgames.com/products/ Fish Lake] [2015], [http://www.7generationgames.com/products/ Forgotten Trail] [2015], [http://www.7generationgames.com/products/ Aztech Games] [forthcoming])<ref>http://www.7generationgames.com/2013/10/20/our-cultural-consultant-on-cultural-content-in-spirit-lake-the-game/</ref>  \n* [[Aboriginal Peoples Television Network]] ([http://animism.com/ Animism] [2010] [http://www.elizabethlapensee.com/#/games/ Mawisowin] [2012], and [http://yourmix.ca/trackjumper.html Your Mix])<ref name=\"elizabethlapensee.com\">http://www.elizabethlapensee.com/#/games/</ref>\n*Aboriginal Territories in Cyberspace [http://www.abtec.org/projects.html Skins Workshops] ([http://skins.abtec.org/skins1.0/ Ots\u00ec:! Rise of the Kanien\u2019keh\u00e1:ka Legends] [2009], [http://skins.abtec.org/skins2.0/ The Adventures of Skahi\u00f2n:hati: Legend of Stone Giant] [2011], [http://skins.abtec.org/skins3.0/ Skahi\u00f2n:hati: Rise of the Kanien\u2019keh\u00e1:ka Legends] [2012], [http://skins.abtec.org/skins4.0/ Ieni\u00e9n:te and the Peacemaker\u2019s Wampum] [2013]<ref>http://www.cbc.ca/m/touch/aboriginal/story/1.2483001</ref>, [http://skins.abtec.org/skins5.0/ He Ao Hou] [2017], [http://skins.abtec.org/skins6.0/ Wao Kanaka: Realm of the People] [2018])\n* Arviat Code Club ([https://scratch.mit.edu/users/Pinnguaq/ Multiple scratch games] [2014-2015])<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pinnguaq.com/nunavut-code-club/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-12-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222151058/http://pinnguaq.com/nunavut-code-club/ |archive-date=2015-12-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Black Cherry Digital Productions ([http://www.pathoftheelders.com/index.php Path of the Elders] [2010] in partnership between the Mushkegowuk Cree, Carlton University, and Pinegrove Productions)<ref>http://www.pathoftheelders.com/aboutus</ref> \n* DarianJ ([http://darianj.itch.io/sleep-guardian Sleep Guardian] [2015])<ref>https://www.facebook.com/skins.workshops/?fref=nf</ref>\n* Elizabeth LaPens\u00e9e When Rivers Were Trails [2019], Thunderbird Strike [2017], Coyote Quest [2017] in collaboration with Loretta Todd, Mikan [2017], Honour Water [2016])<ref name=\"elizabethlapensee.com\"/>, Gathering Native Foods [2014] in collaboration with Hibulb Cultural Center, [http://survivance.org/invaders/ Invaders] [2015] with art by Steven Paul Judd and music by [[Trevino Brings Plenty]], [http://www.survivance.org/wesing/ Ninagamomin ji-nanaandawi'iwe] (We Sing for Healing) [2015], Survivance [2011], ([http://www.abtec.org/blog/?p=436 Techno Medicine Wheel] [2008] in collaboration with Cease Wyss \n* Green Circle Productions ([https://manidoonsuglittlespirits.wordpress.com/ Manidoonsug: Little Spirits] [forthcoming] in consultation with Mississauga New Credit and Annishinabe groups around the GTA<ref name=\"pinnguaq.com\"/>\n* Julia Keren-Detar ([http://mushroom11.com/ Mushroom 11])<ref>http://www.sbs.com.au/nitv/nitv-news/article/2017/04/20/video-games-encourage-indigenous-cultural-expression</ref>\n* Minority Media ([http://www.weareminority.com/spirits-of-spring/ Spirits of Spring] [2014])<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rezolutionpictures.com/new-cree-video-game-spirits-of-spring-featured-in-best-new-games-on-apple-store-in-over-130-countries/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-12-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222103451/http://www.rezolutionpictures.com/new-cree-video-game-spirits-of-spring-featured-in-best-new-games-on-apple-store-in-over-130-countries/ |archive-date=2015-12-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Ogoki ([http://www.ogokilearning.com/native-american-language-apps/ Multiple Language Apps] [2012-2015], [http://www.ogokilearning.com/native-american-language-apps/ Babaamosedaa Let's Go for a Walk] [2014], [http://www.ogokilearning.com/native-american-language-apps/ Brokenhead Bingo] [2015], and [http://www.ogokilearning.com/native-american-language-apps/ Rez Bomb] [2015])<ref>https://itunes.apple.com/ca/developer/ogoki-learning-systems-inc./id477459819</ref> \n* [http://pinnguaq.com/ Pinnguaq] ([http://pinnguaq.com/singuistics/ Singuistics] [2013] in collaboration with Elizabeth LaPens\u00e9e, [http://pinnguaq.com/art-alive/ Art Alive] [2015], [http://qalupalik.com/ Qalupalik] [forthcoming])<ref>http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/pangnirtung-nunavut-game-studio-brings-work-of-pudlo-pudlat-to-life-1.3121713</ref>\n* Raindrop Games ([http://www.arrivalgame.com/content/villagekasike.htm Arrival: Village Kasike] [2012] partnered with Roberto Mukaro Borrero and the United Confederation of Taino People<ref>http://uctp.blogspot.ca/2012_11_01_archive.html</ref> \n* Revolve ([http://revolve.ca/work/music-mogul Music Mogul] [2014] with extensive content by Indigenous musicians including [[A Tribe Called Red]], [[Elisapie]], [[Joey Stylez]], [http://music.cbc.ca/#!/artists/Madeskimo Madeskimo], and [[Red City Radio|Red City]]<ref>http://www.cbc.ca/news/aboriginal/music-mogul-designed-to-teach-indigenous-students-business-skills-1.2944805</ref> \n* Ubisoft ([[Assassin's Creed III]] [2012] in consultation with Thomas Deer and voice acting from [[Noah Watts]]<ref>http://www.abtec.org/blog/?p=381</ref>)\n* [[Upper One Games]] ([[Never Alone (video game)|Never Alone]] [2014])<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/sep/29/never-alone-alaskas-indigenous-game-never-alone-teaches-cooperation-through-stories</ref>\n* [http://virtualsonglines.com.au/ Virtual Songlines] ([http://virtualsonglines.com.au/media/ Irene\u2019s World] [forthcoming], [http://virtualsonglines.com.au/media/ Vincent\u2019s World] [forthcoming], [http://virtualsonglines.com.au/media/ Virtual Warrane II] [forthcoming], [http://virtualsonglines.com.au/media/ Virtual Meanjin] [forthcoming]) \n* [http://www.wisdomoftheelders.org/ Wisdom of the Elders] ([http://survivance.org/ Survivance] [2011])<ref>http://www.neliufpe.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/13.pdf</ref>\n* [http://yijalayala.bighart.org/about/ Yijala Yala Productions], part of [[Big hART]] ([http://www.yijalayala.bighart.org/lovepunks/ Love Punks] [2012])<ref>http://ca.ign.com/articles/2015/01/16/the-rise-of-indigenous-storytelling-in-games</ref>\n* Guilherme Meneses ([https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-news-from-elsewhere-35706657 Huni Kuin] [2016] in a collaboration with the Kanixaw\u00e1 tribe of Brazil and Peru)<ref>http://mashable.com/2016/03/07/indigenous-video-game-huni-kuin/#wH5z.5wtnOqU</ref>\n\n== Indigenous people working in the gaming industry == \nIndigenous people work on a range of video game projects from large blockbusters to small indie collaborations. Many of these individuals are also creating other artistic content such as comics, board games, machinima, and fine art.\n\nMany Indigenous people working in video games are running their own studios or solo practices such as [http://www.achimogames.ca Achimostawinan Games], an Indigenous game studio owned and operated by [[M\u00e9tis]] video game designer Meagan Byrne. (Meagan is best known for her work [https://byrneout.itch.io/wanisinowin-lost Wanisinowin | Lost]). Some have been working in the [[Video game industry]] for years, such as [[Allen Turner (game designer)]] or [[John Romero]] ([[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]]). Some work as both creator and academic, such as game developer and scholar [[Elizabeth LaPens\u00e9e]] (Anishinaabe and M\u00e9tis), who has had a role in creating games such as When Rivers Were Trails, [https://www.thunderbirdstrike.com/ Thunderbird Strike], [http://www.honourwater.com/about Honour Water] and [http://www.digiart21.org/art/invaders Invaders], which merge interactive media and Indigenous ways of knowing.\n\n* Allen Turner ([[Stubbs the Zombie]], [[Hail to the Chimp]], [[Guilty Party (video game)|Disney's Guilty Party]], Marvel XP)<ref name=\"linkedin.com\"/>\n* Ashlee Bird, creator of [https://abird.itch.io/one-small-step One Small Step] and [https://abird.itch.io/imaginenative-gallery-submission Full of Birds]\n* Darrick Glen Baxter, founder of Ogoki (Multiple Language Apps, Alien Bug Attack, Babaamosedaa Let's Go for a Walk, Brokenhead Bingo, Elfs Defence, Rez Bomb, Spike Flyer, Spring Shoes Jump Better)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ogokilearning.com/about-ogoki-learning-systems-learning-president-bio/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-12-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222131248/http://www.ogokilearning.com/about-ogoki-learning-systems-learning-president-bio/ |archive-date=2015-12-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Elizabeth LaPens\u00e9e]] (When Rivers Were Trails, Thunderbird Strike, Invaders, Ninagamomin ji-nanaandawi'iwe, Survivance)<ref name=\"elizabethlapensee.com\"/>  \n* Ernest Webb ([[Papo & Yo]], Spirits of Spring)<ref>http://www.nationnews.ca/moving-in-a-new-direction/</ref>\n* Jamie Tucker ([[Lovers in a Dangerous Spacetime]])<ref>https://tworowtimes.com/art-and-culture/first-nations-comics-and-video-games-draw-a-crowd/</ref>\n*[https://www.jesseholt.com/ Jesse Holt] Audio Designer and Composer previous in-house at DoubleDown Interactive, [[GameHouse]], Absolute Hero Games, Presence Labs, and more.\n* [[John Romero]] ([[Wolfenstein 3D]], [[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]], [[Quake (video game)|Quake]])<ref name=\"usgamer\">http://www.usgamer.net/articles/more-than-shamans-and-savages-american-indians-and-game-development</ref> \n* Manuel Marcano ([[BioShock]], [[The Darkness (video game)|The Darkness]], [[Max Payne 3]], Treachery in Beatdown City)<ref name=\"usgamer\"/>\n* Maru Nihoniho, owner of Metia Interactive (Cube)<ref>http://www.maorifuturemakers.com/maru-nihoniho-games-developer</ref>\n* Maize Longboat, creator of [https://maizelongboat.itch.io/terra-nova Terra/Nova]\n* Meagan Byrne, owner of [http://www.achimogames.ca Achimostawinan Games] and original developer of the [[imagineNATIVE]] iNDigital Space. (Hill Agency: PURITY&decay [forthcoming])\n* [https://nathanpowlesslynes.itch.io/ Nathan Powless-Lynes], Mohawk game designer \n* Renee Nejo (Ever Jane, Blood Quantum [forthcoming])\n* [https://www.linkedin.com/in/stephane-nepton-88ba396/ '''St\u00e9phane Nepton :  Innu VFX Artist'''] (Star-Wars, game of thrones, Far cry 5, gear of war 5 etc...) and cofounder of [https://www.facebook.com/uhulabosnomades/ '''Uhu labos nomades'''];an initiative whose mission is to support the perseverance of schooling among Aboriginal youth through the digital arts; Ar, Vr, videogame, special effects, 3d mapping.\n\n== Games translated into Indigenous languages ==\nThere have also been numerous video games translated into Indigenous languages. For example, Pinnguaq has localized osmosis, Ittle Dew and Beneath the Floes.<ref>http://pinnguaq.com/localization/</ref> Both the video games made in the Skins Hawai\u2018i-based workshops, [http://skins.abtec.org/skins5.0/ <nowiki>He Ao Hou [2017]</nowiki>]  and [http://skins.abtec.org/skins6.0/ Wao Kanaka: Realm of the People] [2018], were designed so that the player can play in \u2018\u014clelo Hawai\u2018i as well as in English. \n\n==Academic studies==\n\nAcademic studies of indigenous video gaming are still infrequent. In 2017, the peer-reviewed open-access Indigenous Studies [[academic journal|journal]] ''Transmotion'' devoted a special issue to the topic.<ref> Transmotion 3:1 (2017) https://journals.kent.ac.uk/index.php/transmotion/issue/view/25</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Race and video games]]\n*[[Indigenous Futurisms]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|32em}}\n\n[[Category:Indigenous peoples]]\n[[Category:Video game culture]]\n", "text_old": "[[Indigenous people]] have a long history of collaborating on the creation of [[video game]]s.<ref name=\"vimeo.com\">https://vimeo.com/128110465</ref> It has only been with the release of [[Never Alone (video game)|Never Alone]] though that broad media attention has been paid to these projects.<ref>A Tribe Called Geek's third podcast called \"Indigenous Gaming\" http://atribecalledgeek.com/tag/video-games/ ; see also http://ca.ign.com/articles/2015/01/16/the-rise-of-indigenous-storytelling-in-games</ref> There have been a growing number of game gatherings and community organizing around Indigenous games happening in the United States and Canada.<ref name=\"linkedin.com\">https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/natives-game-dev-gathering-elizabeth-lapens%C3%A9e</ref><ref name=\"pinnguaq.com\">http://pinnguaq.com/blog-all/120-evening-celebrate</ref> Indigenous creators of video games have been featured in the DIGITAL MEDIA ART+CADE as part of imagineNATIVE<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.imaginenative.org/home/node/4546 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-12-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927051603/http://www.imaginenative.org/home/node/4546 |archive-date=2015-09-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and in ''Memories of the Future/Souvenirs du futur'' at SAW Video Media Art Centre in Ottawa.<ref>http://www.sawvideo.com/event/memories-future</ref> Many early video games that depicted Indigenous people misrepresented them and perpetuated negative stereotypes (see [[Custer's Revenge]]).<ref>http://www.cbc.ca/news/aboriginal/indigenous-video-game-designer-takes-stand-against-custer-s-revenge-1.2851104</ref> Video games created by Indigenous people enable the creators to self-determine how they are represented<ref>http://www.content.alternative.ac.nz/index.php/alternative/article/view/274</ref>.\n\n== Games where Indigenous people represent themselves ==\nIndigenous people have been involved in a range of projects where they have the opportunity to depict themselves. These games range in the style of the collaboration from games that consult with a single Indigenous person to games that are entirely developed and designed by Indigenous people.<ref name=\"vimeo.com\"/> \n* [http://www.7generationgames.com/ 7 Generation Games] ([http://www.7generationgames.com/products/ Spirit Lake] [2013], [http://www.7generationgames.com/products/ Fish Lake] [2015], [http://www.7generationgames.com/products/ Forgotten Trail] [2015], [http://www.7generationgames.com/products/ Aztech Games] [forthcoming])<ref>http://www.7generationgames.com/2013/10/20/our-cultural-consultant-on-cultural-content-in-spirit-lake-the-game/</ref>  \n* [[Aboriginal Peoples Television Network]] ([http://animism.com/ Animism] [2010] [http://www.elizabethlapensee.com/#/games/ Mawisowin] [2012], and [http://yourmix.ca/trackjumper.html Your Mix])<ref name=\"elizabethlapensee.com\">http://www.elizabethlapensee.com/#/games/</ref>\n*Aboriginal Territories in Cyberspace * [http://www.abtec.org/projects.html Skins Workshops] ([http://skins.abtec.org/skins1.0/ Ots\u00ec:! Rise of the Kanien\u2019keh\u00e1:ka Legends] [2009], [http://skins.abtec.org/skins2.0/ The Adventures of Skahi\u00f2n:hati: Legend of Stone Giant] [2011], [http://skins.abtec.org/skins3.0/ Skahi\u00f2n:hati: Rise of the Kanien\u2019keh\u00e1:ka Legends] [2012], [http://skins.abtec.org/skins4.0/ Ieni\u00e9n:te and the Peacemaker\u2019s Wampum] [2013]<ref>http://www.cbc.ca/m/touch/aboriginal/story/1.2483001</ref>, [http://skins.abtec.org/skins5.0/ He Ao Hou] [2017], [http://skins.abtec.org/skins6.0/ Wao Kanaka: Realm of the People] [2018])\n* Arviat Code Club ([https://scratch.mit.edu/users/Pinnguaq/ Multiple scratch games] [2014-2015])<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pinnguaq.com/nunavut-code-club/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-12-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222151058/http://pinnguaq.com/nunavut-code-club/ |archive-date=2015-12-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Black Cherry Digital Productions ([http://www.pathoftheelders.com/index.php Path of the Elders] [2010] in partnership between the Mushkegowuk Cree, Carlton University, and Pinegrove Productions)<ref>http://www.pathoftheelders.com/aboutus</ref> \n* DarianJ ([http://darianj.itch.io/sleep-guardian Sleep Guardian] [2015])<ref>https://www.facebook.com/skins.workshops/?fref=nf</ref>\n* Elizabeth LaPens\u00e9e When Rivers Were Trails [2019], Thunderbird Strike [2017], Coyote Quest [2017] in collaboration with Loretta Todd, Mikan [2017], Honour Water [2016])<ref name=\"elizabethlapensee.com\"/>, Gathering Native Foods [2014] in collaboration with Hibulb Cultural Center, [http://survivance.org/invaders/ Invaders] [2015] with art by Steven Paul Judd and music by [[Trevino Brings Plenty]], [http://www.survivance.org/wesing/ Ninagamomin ji-nanaandawi'iwe] (We Sing for Healing) [2015], Survivance [2011], ([http://www.abtec.org/blog/?p=436 Techno Medicine Wheel] [2008] in collaboration with Cease Wyss \n* Green Circle Productions ([https://manidoonsuglittlespirits.wordpress.com/ Manidoonsug: Little Spirits] [forthcoming] in consultation with Mississauga New Credit and Annishinabe groups around the GTA<ref name=\"pinnguaq.com\"/>\n* Julia Keren-Detar ([http://mushroom11.com/ Mushroom 11])<ref>http://www.sbs.com.au/nitv/nitv-news/article/2017/04/20/video-games-encourage-indigenous-cultural-expression</ref>\n* Minority Media ([http://www.weareminority.com/spirits-of-spring/ Spirits of Spring] [2014])<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rezolutionpictures.com/new-cree-video-game-spirits-of-spring-featured-in-best-new-games-on-apple-store-in-over-130-countries/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-12-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222103451/http://www.rezolutionpictures.com/new-cree-video-game-spirits-of-spring-featured-in-best-new-games-on-apple-store-in-over-130-countries/ |archive-date=2015-12-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Ogoki ([http://www.ogokilearning.com/native-american-language-apps/ Multiple Language Apps] [2012-2015], [http://www.ogokilearning.com/native-american-language-apps/ Babaamosedaa Let's Go for a Walk] [2014], [http://www.ogokilearning.com/native-american-language-apps/ Brokenhead Bingo] [2015], and [http://www.ogokilearning.com/native-american-language-apps/ Rez Bomb] [2015])<ref>https://itunes.apple.com/ca/developer/ogoki-learning-systems-inc./id477459819</ref> \n* [http://pinnguaq.com/ Pinnguaq] ([http://pinnguaq.com/singuistics/ Singuistics] [2013] in collaboration with Elizabeth LaPens\u00e9e, [http://pinnguaq.com/art-alive/ Art Alive] [2015], [http://qalupalik.com/ Qalupalik] [forthcoming])<ref>http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/pangnirtung-nunavut-game-studio-brings-work-of-pudlo-pudlat-to-life-1.3121713</ref>\n* Raindrop Games ([http://www.arrivalgame.com/content/villagekasike.htm Arrival: Village Kasike] [2012] partnered with Roberto Mukaro Borrero and the United Confederation of Taino People<ref>http://uctp.blogspot.ca/2012_11_01_archive.html</ref> \n* Revolve ([http://revolve.ca/work/music-mogul Music Mogul] [2014] with extensive content by Indigenous musicians including [[A Tribe Called Red]], [[Elisapie]], [[Joey Stylez]], [http://music.cbc.ca/#!/artists/Madeskimo Madeskimo], and [[Red City Radio|Red City]]<ref>http://www.cbc.ca/news/aboriginal/music-mogul-designed-to-teach-indigenous-students-business-skills-1.2944805</ref> \n* Ubisoft ([[Assassin's Creed III]] [2012] in consultation with Thomas Deer and voice acting from [[Noah Watts]]<ref>http://www.abtec.org/blog/?p=381</ref>)\n* [[Upper One Games]] ([[Never Alone (video game)|Never Alone]] [2014])<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/sep/29/never-alone-alaskas-indigenous-game-never-alone-teaches-cooperation-through-stories</ref>\n* [http://virtualsonglines.com.au/ Virtual Songlines] ([http://virtualsonglines.com.au/media/ Irene\u2019s World] [forthcoming], [http://virtualsonglines.com.au/media/ Vincent\u2019s World] [forthcoming], [http://virtualsonglines.com.au/media/ Virtual Warrane II] [forthcoming], [http://virtualsonglines.com.au/media/ Virtual Meanjin] [forthcoming]) \n* [http://www.wisdomoftheelders.org/ Wisdom of the Elders] ([http://survivance.org/ Survivance] [2011])<ref>http://www.neliufpe.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/13.pdf</ref>\n* [http://yijalayala.bighart.org/about/ Yijala Yala Productions], part of [[Big hART]] ([http://www.yijalayala.bighart.org/lovepunks/ Love Punks] [2012])<ref>http://ca.ign.com/articles/2015/01/16/the-rise-of-indigenous-storytelling-in-games</ref>\n* Guilherme Meneses ([https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-news-from-elsewhere-35706657 Huni Kuin] [2016] in a collaboration with the Kanixaw\u00e1 tribe of Brazil and Peru)<ref>http://mashable.com/2016/03/07/indigenous-video-game-huni-kuin/#wH5z.5wtnOqU</ref>\n\n== Indigenous people working in the gaming industry == \nIndigenous people work on a range of video game projects from large blockbusters to small indie collaborations. Many of these individuals are also creating other artistic content such as comics, board games, machinima, and fine art.\n\nMany Indigenous people working in video games are running their own studios or solo practices such as [http://www.achimogames.ca Achimostawinan Games], an Indigenous game studio owned and operated by [[M\u00e9tis]] video game designer Meagan Byrne. (Meagan is best known for her work [https://byrneout.itch.io/wanisinowin-lost Wanisinowin | Lost]). Some have been working in the [[Video game industry]] for years, such as [[Allen Turner (game designer)]] or [[John Romero]] ([[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]]). Some work as both creator and academic, such as game developer and scholar [[Elizabeth LaPens\u00e9e]] (Anishinaabe and M\u00e9tis), who has had a role in creating games such as When Rivers Were Trails, [https://www.thunderbirdstrike.com/ Thunderbird Strike], [http://www.honourwater.com/about Honour Water] and [http://www.digiart21.org/art/invaders Invaders], which merge interactive media and Indigenous ways of knowing.\n\n* Allen Turner ([[Stubbs the Zombie]], [[Hail to the Chimp]], [[Guilty Party (video game)|Disney's Guilty Party]], Marvel XP)<ref name=\"linkedin.com\"/>\n* Ashlee Bird, creator of [https://abird.itch.io/one-small-step One Small Step] and [https://abird.itch.io/imaginenative-gallery-submission Full of Birds]\n* Darrick Glen Baxter, founder of Ogoki (Multiple Language Apps, Alien Bug Attack, Babaamosedaa Let's Go for a Walk, Brokenhead Bingo, Elfs Defence, Rez Bomb, Spike Flyer, Spring Shoes Jump Better)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ogokilearning.com/about-ogoki-learning-systems-learning-president-bio/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-12-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222131248/http://www.ogokilearning.com/about-ogoki-learning-systems-learning-president-bio/ |archive-date=2015-12-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Elizabeth LaPens\u00e9e]] (When Rivers Were Trails, Thunderbird Strike, Invaders, Ninagamomin ji-nanaandawi'iwe, Survivance)<ref name=\"elizabethlapensee.com\"/>  \n* Ernest Webb ([[Papo & Yo]], Spirits of Spring)<ref>http://www.nationnews.ca/moving-in-a-new-direction/</ref>\n* Jamie Tucker ([[Lovers in a Dangerous Spacetime]])<ref>https://tworowtimes.com/art-and-culture/first-nations-comics-and-video-games-draw-a-crowd/</ref>\n*[https://www.jesseholt.com/ Jesse Holt] Audio Designer and Composer previous in-house at DoubleDown Interactive, [[GameHouse]], Absolute Hero Games, Presence Labs, and more.\n* [[John Romero]] ([[Wolfenstein 3D]], [[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]], [[Quake (video game)|Quake]])<ref name=\"usgamer\">http://www.usgamer.net/articles/more-than-shamans-and-savages-american-indians-and-game-development</ref> \n* Manuel Marcano ([[BioShock]], [[The Darkness (video game)|The Darkness]], [[Max Payne 3]], Treachery in Beatdown City)<ref name=\"usgamer\"/>\n* Maru Nihoniho, owner of Metia Interactive (Cube)<ref>http://www.maorifuturemakers.com/maru-nihoniho-games-developer</ref>\n* Maize Longboat, creator of [https://maizelongboat.itch.io/terra-nova Terra/Nova]\n* Meagan Byrne, owner of [http://www.achimogames.ca Achimostawinan Games] and original developer of the [[imagineNATIVE]] iNDigital Space. (Hill Agency: PURITY&decay [forthcoming])\n* [https://nathanpowlesslynes.itch.io/ Nathan Powless-Lynes], Mohawk game designer \n* Renee Nejo (Ever Jane, Blood Quantum [forthcoming])\n* [https://www.linkedin.com/in/stephane-nepton-88ba396/ '''St\u00e9phane Nepton :  Innu VFX Artist'''] (Star-Wars, game of thrones, Far cry 5, gear of war 5 etc...) and cofounder of [https://www.facebook.com/uhulabosnomades/ '''Uhu labos nomades'''];an initiative whose mission is to support the perseverance of schooling among Aboriginal youth through the digital arts; Ar, Vr, videogame, special effects, 3d mapping.\n\n== Games translated into Indigenous languages ==\nThere have also been numerous video games translated into Indigenous languages. For example, Pinnguaq has localized osmosis, Ittle Dew and Beneath the Floes.<ref>http://pinnguaq.com/localization/</ref> Both the video games made in the Skins Hawai\u2018i-based workshops, [http://skins.abtec.org/skins5.0/ <nowiki>He Ao Hou [2017]</nowiki>]  and [http://skins.abtec.org/skins6.0/ Wao Kanaka: Realm of the People] [2018], were designed so that the player can play in \u2018\u014clelo Hawai\u2018i as well as in English. \n\n==Academic studies==\n\nAcademic studies of indigenous video gaming are still infrequent. In 2017, the peer-reviewed open-access Indigenous Studies [[academic journal|journal]] ''Transmotion'' devoted a special issue to the topic.<ref> Transmotion 3:1 (2017) https://journals.kent.ac.uk/index.php/transmotion/issue/view/25</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Race and video games]]\n*[[Indigenous Futurisms]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|32em}}\n\n[[Category:Indigenous peoples]]\n[[Category:Video game culture]]\n", "name_user": "Dnakmigziwnan", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indigenous_people_in_video_games"}
